<DOC><DOCNO> AP890404-0171 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 1953EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-04 0513</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0528</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms in the Southeast; Snow in the Rockies</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A band of thunderstorms whipped through the Southeast onTuesday, with tornadoes snapping trees and power lines in Georgiaand Alabama. A storm stalled over Colorado dropped more snow andraised the risk of avalanches.   In Haubstadt, Ind., divers searched two rain-swollen creeks forthe body of a 16-month-old toddler swept away after the family carstalled on a flooded road. An Evansville woman was electrocuted bya fallen power line.   Tornadoes dipped across north Georgia Tuesday afternoon,damaging homes and buildings, downing power lines and uprootingtrees. Power outages were widespread.   A Georgia Power spokesman said approximately 26,000 customerswere without power.   In Alabama, thunderstorms packing 70 mph wind ripped down treesand knocked out electrical power to some 18,000 homes. State andlocal police reported many homes with roof damage and some ruralroads closed by fallen trees.   A tornado watch was posted Tuesday night over parts of Georgia,North Carolina, Tennessee, Mississippi, Alabama and Florida.   In Colorado, advisories were posted for an additional 6 inchesof snow Tuesday and wind gusting to 40 mph across the northern andcentral mountains. The storm has dumped more than 6 feet of snowduring the past week, increasing the avalanche danger.   Breckenridge has reported 73 inches of snow during the pastseven days, while Copper Mountain reported 62 inches and Mary Jane58 inches.   Showers were scattered over central and southeast New Englandinto northeast New York.   Rain continued along the northern Pacific Coast. Snowshowerswere scattered in Montana, Wyoming and Nebraska.   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 2{ inches at Greenwood, Miss., and 1\ inches at Columbus,Miss.   The low temperature for the nation Tuesday morning was 7 degreesbelow zero at Yellowstone, Wyo.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Long Beach,Oceanside, Ontario and Thermal, Calif.   In Los Angeles, a 79-year-old record fell Tuesday when thetemperature hit 100. Lifeguards scrambled for help as residents hitthe beaches for relief.   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstormsfrom central Florida across eastern Pennsylvania and New Jersey;rainshowers from the remainder of Pennsylvania across the lowerGreat Lakes, New England and much of lower Michigan, and rain fromnorthwest Montana across the northern Pacific Coast.   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s over the Great Lakes,Minnesota, North Dakota and northeast Montana; in the 50s and 60sfrom New England across much of the Virginias, the Ohio Valley, theTennessee Valley, northern portions of the states from Georgiaacross Mississippi, from Iowa across Arkansas, over the remainderof the northern and central Plains, Oklahoma, the Rockies, thenorthern half of the Plateau, and the northern Pacific Coast; inthe 80s over the Florida Peninsula; with 80s and 90s from southernNew Mexico across the southern third of inland California; near 100over the desert Southwest, and in the 70s over the rest of thenation.</TEXT></DOC>